{
  "texts": [
    "In such settings, regularization is required to obtain stable approximate inverses.",
    "Two common regularization approaches are Tikhonov regularization, where T -1 ≈ (T ⋆ T + λI) -1 T ⋆, λ > 0, and spectral cut-off, which truncates the Singular Value Decomposition (SVD) [14].When T is compact (and therefore it admits a countable sequence of singular values), the degree of ill-posedness of the inverse problem is characterized by the decay rate of these singular values.",
    "Since the singular values of T -1 are the reciprocals of those of T, faster decay implies worse ill-posedness.The NPIV problem can be viewed as particularly challenging, as in addition to the ill-posedness of the operator T, one must also estimate it from data.",
    "We now introduce a sufficient condition for compactness of T. Assumption 2.",
    "The joint distribution π XZ is dominated by the product measure π X ⊗ π Z, and its Radon-Nikodym derivative, or \"density\", p.= dπ XZ dπ X ⊗π Z belongs to L 2 (X × Z, π X ⊗ π Z).Assumption 2 is standard in the NPIV literature (Assumption A.1 in [11])."
  ]
}